21. All the powers thus gathered in the hands os the prince were recognized powers os Roman magistrates. The Empire as a system os govemment did not, in its first years, contain a single principle which had not already existed under the Repub lic. What was novel was the combining oi all these powers in the hands os one rnan as a permanent possession. The prince was a magistrate, created by law, aud amenable to law3 the new magistracy fitted perfectly into the republican scheme. But it was an assemblage os powers so extraordinary and controlling that its possessor was in practice raised sar above every other person or body ol persons in the state. (See the interesting letter of Tiberius, III. 53.) It may be compared to the dictatorship os the early Republic, which consisted in the bestowal os extraordinary power upon one man, to meet an extraordinary crisis. The crisis had now become chronic, and the dictatorship was made permanent. (See Seeley's first lecture on Roman Imperialism.)
